Background

Were going to explore a large data set or traffic crashes to learn about what factors are connected with injuries. We will use data from the city of Chicagos open data portal. (This activity is derived from a blog post by Julia Silge)

years_ago <- mdy("01/01/2022") # data from last 2 years. May take time to load!
crash_url <- glue::glue("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Transportation/Traffic-Crashes-Crashes/85ca-t3if?$where=CRASH_DATE >= '{years_ago}'")
crash_raw <- as_tibble(read.socrata(crash_url)) # a new way to read in data, don't worry about it!

This dataset is pretty crazy! Take a look at it in the viewer, and then lets do some data munging to get it into a nicer form.

-create a variable called injuries which indicates if the crash involved injuries or not. -create an unknown category for missing report_types -decide which other variables to keep

crash <- crash_raw %>%
  arrange(desc(crash_date)) %>%
  transmute(
    crash_date,
    injuries = as.factor(if_else(injuries_total > 0, "injuries", "none")),
    report_type = as.factor(replace(crash_raw$report_type, crash_raw$report_type=="", "UNKNOWN")),
    latitude, longitude,
    prim_contributory_cause,
    sec_contributory_cause,
    crash_month = as.factor(crash_month),
    weather_condition,
    lighting_condition,
    posted_speed_limit,
    injuries_total
  )

Exploratory Data Analysis

Heres a few questions to get you started.

  1. Take a look at crashes by latitude and longitude, colored by injuries. What do you notice?

There doesnt seem to be much correlation between the location of a crash and whether injuries were sustained. The crashes with injuries and crashes without are distributed evenly across Chicago.

  1. What are the most common contributing factors to a crash?

Failing to yield the right of way was the leading cause of crashes.

  1. How do crashes vary month by month? Compare crashes by month in 2022 to 2023.

Crashes seem to peak in May and October, with higher numbers of crashes in the summer and fewer in the winter. There are small differences between 2022 and 2023, but they generally seem to be negligible.

  1. Are crashes more likely to cause injuries when it is rainy and dark? Use the variables weather_condition and lighting_condition to explore.

The most frequent conditions to cause injuries are clear days, likely because thats when the most people are driving.

  1. Choose a question you want to explore, and create an appropriate visual.

Do crashes at higher speeds result in more injuries?

According to this graph, the crashes with the most injuries seem to be more frequent at speeds around 30 mph, right in the middle. This may be because more streets in Chicago have moderate speed limits than higher speed limits. It could also be due to the fact that there are pedestrians on slower city streets unlike on fast highways, so more pedestrians are likely to be hit on a 30 mph road than a highway.
